%p#sudo Linux always has a user named root who has many privileges.

%p I can use sudo to ask root to run commands for me.

%p In that case sudo is a verb.

%p If root does what I ask then I have sudo privilege and in that case sudo is a noun.

%p If I want to give sudo privilege to bob I should run a command like this:
.syntax
  %pre
    %code.bash sudo usermod -G sudo bob


%p Another way to give sudo privilege to bob is login as root and run this command:
.syntax
  %pre
    %code.bash usermod -G sudo bob

%p#su I have three ways to login as root:
.syntax
  %pre
    %code.bash su

%p This way is more ... complete:
.syntax
  %pre
    %code.bash su -
    
%p And, this way is more ... complete:
.syntax
  %pre
    %code.bash ssh root@localhost
    
%p Also I can use su to login as bob:
.syntax
  %pre
    %code.bash su - bob

%p#sshfolder Usually on Linux every user has an ssh-folder:
.syntax
  %pre
    %code.bash
      su - bob
      mkdir -p  ~/.ssh
      chmod 755 ~/.ssh

%p#publickey Usually on Linux every user has public key and private key.
%p#privatekey bob can create public key and private key:
.syntax
  %pre
    %code.bash
      su - bob
      ssh-keygen -t rsa
      ls -l .ssh/id_rsa
      ls -l .ssh/id_rsa.pub

%p The file .ssh/id_rsa is like a key I carry in my pocket. It should be private.

%p
  The file .ssh/id_rsa.pub is like a lock in my car door. It is exposed to the public.
  The file .ssh/id_rsa.pub is called a public key.

%p#authorized_keys bob can give id_rsa.pub to dan and dan can add id_rsa.pub to ~dan/.ssh/authorized_keys:
.syntax
  %pre
    %code.bash sudo cat ~bob/.ssh/id_rsa.pub >> ~dan/.ssh/authorized_keys

%p Now bob has permission to login as dan:
.syntax
  %pre
    %code.bash sudo ssh dan@localhost

%p#pemkey A pem key is a private key I get from AWS.

%p I like to keep my pem keys in ~dan/.ssh/

%p To use a pem key I create a file called ~dan/.ssh/config

%p I put syntax like this in the file:
.syntax
  %pre
    =render 'class02ec22'

%p Then I issue a simple shell command to login:
.syntax
  %pre
    %code.bash ssh ub170

%p#keypermissions Sometimes keys will fail due to improper permissions.

%p If I suspect improper permissions on my keys, I issue commands like this:

.syntax
  %pre
    %code.bash
      cd ~/.ssh/
      chmod 700 .
      chmod 700 ..
      chmod 600 authorized_keys
      chmod 600 *.pem
      chmod 600 id_rsa
      chmod 644 id_rsa.pub

